rdt.title: Protocol
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

! The cascade-palette protocol

A cascade is a graph of ''entries'' (root-stage items) and ''actions'' (items in the per-entity-type action menu). The engine walks this graph as the user types and presses ''→ / Space / Esc / Enter''. Adding a new cascade edge is one tiddler.

Each tiddler has a tag and a small set of `ca-*` fields. The engine reads them at every palette-open.

! Tags

* ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry`'' — root-stage menu item
* ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action`'' — appears in the action menu for one entity type

! Fields

;`ca-name`
:Display text in the result row. Required.
;`ca-hint`
:Subtitle / right-aligned hint text. Optional.
;`ca-icon`
:Single character or emoji shown to the left of the name. Optional.
;`ca-kind`
:`leaf` or `drill`. Default: `leaf`. A leaf fires `ca-actions` on Enter and closes the palette. A drill pushes a new stage on Right-arrow or Enter.
;`ca-order`
:Numeric sort key. Default: `100`. Lower numbers appear higher in the list. Ties break by `ca-name` (alphabetical).
;`ca-entity-type` (actions only)
:Catalogue-path binding. The action surfaces on rows whose emitting layer declared `ca-layer-row-entity-type` matching this value (e.g. an Entries-view drill into a typed picker). Use ''`*`'' to make the action global (appears for any entity type). Tree-view rows have no bound entityType — to reach them either (a) install a type-system plugin that sets `$:/config/rimir/cascade-palette/entity-type-field` (e.g. `rimir/kind` ≥ 0.1.50 sets it to `kind.type`, making `ca-entity-type: <X>` auto-match any tiddler with `kind.type: <X>` in any view), or (b) add a per-action `ca-applies` filter.
;`ca-applies` (actions only, optional)
:Filter-path discovery. Filter evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the row's title. Non-empty result ⇒ the action surfaces on that row in ''any'' view — Entries, By Namespace, By parent, Hybrid, custom. Lets actions reach tree-view rows that have no bound entityType, and lets the same action register on multiple ad-hoc tiddler shapes without ceremony. Example: `ca-applies: [<currentTiddler>get[kind]match[person]]` surfaces wherever a tiddler's kind is `person`, regardless of how it was reached. Combines with `ca-entity-type` — both paths union, deduplicated by action title.
;`ca-default` (actions only)
:Set to ''`yes`'' on the action that should fire when the user hits Enter on a dynamic entity result (without first opening the action menu via Right or Space). Usually the ''Open'' action. Exactly one per entity type.
;`ca-action-when` (actions only, optional)
:Refinement filter — narrows whichever discovery path (entity-type or `ca-applies`) matched. Evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the picked entity. Non-empty result ⇒ the action is applicable for that specific tiddler. Empty / missing filter ⇒ always applicable. Use to hide actions that don't make sense per instance — e.g. `[<currentTiddler>!has[done]]` shows "Mark done" only for tiddlers without a `done` field.
;`ca-actions` (leaf only)
:Wikitext fired on Enter. Receives `<<picked>>` and `<<parent-picked>>` in scope. Typically a single action widget like `<$action-navigate $to=<<picked>>/>` or a setfield.
;`ca-next-scope` (drill only)
:Filter expression for the next stage's items. Can reference `<<query>>` (current input), `<<parent-picked>>`, and `<<stage-N-picked>>`. Examples: `[rrt.type[person]search<query>]`, `[[low]] [[normal]] [[high]] [[critical]]`, `[<parent-picked>get[team-member-of]enlist-input[]]`.
;`ca-next-title` (drill only)
:Title shown in the breadcrumb for the new stage. Can use `<<parent-picked>>` to reference what was picked.
;`ca-next-entity-type` (drill only)
:Sets the next stage's entity type. The engine uses this to discover action tiddlers when the user opens the action menu on a result (Right-arrow or Space). Omit when the picker shouldn't have its own action menu (e.g. an enum picker that should just fire a setfield).
;`ca-next-default-action` (drill only)
:Wikitext fired when the user picks an item in the new stage if no entity-type default action exists. Typical use: an enum picker where the items are bare strings and you want Enter to act on the parent.

! Substitution variables

Available inside `ca-next-scope`, `ca-actions`, and `ca-next-default-action`:

;`<<query>>`
:Current text typed in the current stage's input. Use to filter the next stage by user input.
;`<<picked>>`
:For ''action invocation'': the title of the item just picked. In an action-menu stage, this is the entity the menu acts on (i.e. the parent-picked). In a filter stage's default action, it's the picked item.
;`<<parent-picked>>`
:Title picked in the parent stage (one back).
;`<<stage-N-picked>>`
:Title picked in stage N (0 = root). For deeper chains.

! Worked example 1 — A leaf entry that opens a fixed tiddler

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/control-panel
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Open Control Panel
ca-kind: leaf
ca-order: 10
ca-actions: <$action-navigate $to="$:/ControlPanel"/>
```

! Worked example 2 — A drill entry into a type-scoped search

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/persons
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Persons
ca-icon: 🙍
ca-kind: drill
ca-order: 30
ca-next-scope: [rrt.type[person]search<query>]
ca-next-title: Persons
ca-next-entity-type: person
```

Right-arrow into "Persons" → palette shows persons filtered by your input. Enter on a person fires the person type's default action (typically Open). Right-arrow (or Space) on a person opens the action menu.

! Worked example 3 — A type's default action (Open)

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/person/open
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: person
ca-name: Open
ca-kind: leaf
ca-default: yes
ca-order: 10
ca-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<picked>>/>
```

! Worked example 4 — A drill action into related entities

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/person/teams
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: person
ca-name: Assigned Teams
ca-kind: drill
ca-order: 20
ca-next-scope: [<parent-picked>get[team-member-of]enlist-input[]search<query>]
ca-next-title: Teams of <<parent-picked>>
ca-next-entity-type: team
```

The chain works: Persons → pick Alice → action menu → Right "Assigned Teams" → stage shows Alice's teams → Right (or Space) on a team to see TEAM actions, or Enter to open the team.

! Worked example 5 — Same action in catalogue ''and'' tree views

To surface the same person-action in the Entries catalogue (via `ca-entity-type`) AND in tree views like ''By namespace'' (via `ca-applies`):

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/person/open
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: person
ca-applies: [<currentTiddler>get[kind]match[person]]
ca-name: Open
ca-kind: leaf
ca-default: yes
ca-order: 10
ca-actions: <$action-statewrap-navigate label=<<picked>> person=<<picked>>/>
```

In ''Entries'' the catalogue path matches on `ca-entity-type: person`. In ''By namespace'' / ''By parent'' the same row has no bound entityType, so the engine evaluates `ca-applies` against the row title; non-empty result ⇒ the action surfaces. Hitting Space on a person tiddler in any tree view now opens the same action menu users see in the catalogue.

A purely filter-bound action (no catalogue presence) just omits `ca-entity-type`:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/has-url/open
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-applies: [<currentTiddler>get[url]prefix[http]]
ca-name: Open URL
ca-kind: leaf
ca-actions: <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-browser-open-url" url={{!!url}}/>
```

This action surfaces on any tiddler with an http-prefixed `url` field, anywhere the user can press Space on it.

! Worked example 6 — Drill-then-act (enum picker)

When you want a sub-pick that just sets a field (no further drilling), use `ca-next-default-action`:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/task/set-priority
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: task
ca-name: Set Priority…
ca-kind: drill
ca-order: 60
ca-next-scope: [[low]] [[normal]] [[high]] [[critical]]
ca-next-title: Priority for <<parent-picked>>
ca-next-default-action: <$action-setfield $tiddler=<<parent-picked>> priority=<<picked>>/>
```

Note: ''no'' `ca-next-entity-type` — the four enum strings aren't entity tiddlers, so we don't want the engine to try to open an action menu when the user picks one. The `ca-next-default-action` fires on Enter.

! Worked example 6 — A toggle setting

Settings appear under the engine's root "Settings" entry. Any tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/setting`'' with `ca-kind: toggle` becomes a toggle row. The row shows a checkbox glyph and the current value; ''Space'' flips it inline (palette stays open), ''Enter'' flips it and closes, ''Shift-Enter'' flips it and stays open.

```
title: $:/plugins/example/settings/auto-refresh
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/setting
ca-name: Auto-refresh stages
ca-kind: toggle
ca-order: 20
ca-bind-tiddler: $:/config/example/auto-refresh
ca-bind-field: text
ca-true-value: yes
ca-false-value: no
```

The binding is scribe-style — pair `ca-bind-tiddler` + `ca-bind-field`. Add `ca-bind-path: prefs,enabled` to bind to a JSON sub-path of the field text instead of the whole field. Defaults: `ca-bind-field: text`, `ca-true-value: yes`, `ca-false-value: no`.

! Worked example 7 — A number setting

`ca-kind: number` shows a numeric value (and, when ''both'' `ca-min` and `ca-max` are set, an inline horizontal slider bar). ''+'' and ''-'' adjust by `ca-step`. ''Shift'' multiplies via `ca-step-medium`, ''Ctrl'' via `ca-step-large`. Value is clamped to [`ca-min`, `ca-max`] on write. Enter closes the palette; Shift-Enter keeps it open (numbers never "fire" — they're just edited).

```
title: $:/plugins/example/settings/page-size
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/setting
ca-name: Page size
ca-kind: number
ca-order: 30
ca-bind-tiddler: $:/config/example/page-size
ca-bind-field: text
ca-min: 5
ca-max: 100
ca-step: 1
ca-step-medium: 5
ca-step-large: 20
ca-default-value: 30
```

''Layout caveat:'' the engine matches the physical keys (`Equal`/`NumpadAdd` for `+`, `Minus`/`NumpadSubtract` for `-`) rather than the produced character, so the same combos work on US, DE, and other layouts. On US layouts where Shift is already required to get `+`, that's already the bare-step gesture; Shift+Shift isn't possible and there's no extra "medium" gesture using `Shift+Plus`. Use the numeric or alternate physical key, or use the `=` key (also matches "+") for finer control.

! Worked example 8 — A text setting

`ca-kind: text` shows the current value on the right. ''Space'' or ''Enter'' pushes the value into the palette's input field for editing — the input becomes a value editor (highlighted background, result list dims), Enter commits the new value back, Esc discards. Use for short strings: hotkey bindings, label overrides, file paths.

''Chaining an action onto the commit:'' `ca-on-commit` fires action wikitext AFTER the value lands (with `<<picked>>` bound to the committed value). Useful for single-shot text rows that need to ''do'' something with the input — e.g. captured key → `$action-createtiddler` — rather than just persist it to a field. `ca-on-commit` works with or without `ca-bind-tiddler`: bind-less rows are pure captures (value lives only in `<<picked>>` for the action).

```
title: $:/plugins/example/settings/hotkey
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/setting
ca-name: Hotkey
ca-kind: text
ca-order: 50
ca-bind-tiddler: $:/config/shortcuts/example-open
ca-bind-field: text
```

Numbers also support this edit gesture — Space on a number row enters the same edit mode, letting you type a value directly instead of nudging with +/-. (Both gestures coexist.)

! Worked example 9 — A global action (applies to any entity type)

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/global/edit
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: *
ca-name: Edit raw tiddler
ca-kind: leaf
ca-order: 200
ca-actions: <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-edit-tiddler" $param=<<picked>>/>
```

! Tips

* Trailing newlines in `.tid` config tiddlers consumed by the engine (especially `$:/config/shortcuts/rimir-cascade-palette-open`) ''break'' parsing — write the body with no terminator and omit the `type` field. See [[feedback-tid-vs-txt-meta]] in `.claude/memory/`.
* Filter operands cannot contain literal `[...]` brackets. To reference a nested filter result in `ca-next-scope`, use variable indirection: `[subfilter<myvar>]` where `myvar` is declared via `<$let>` in the calling context (or assemble the subfilter in a `\function`).
* `<<picked>>` is empty inside `ca-next-scope` (nothing has been picked in the new stage yet) — use `<<parent-picked>>` to scope the new stage by the previous pick.
* If your action depends on TW's navigator (`<$action-navigate>`, `tm-edit-tiddler`, `tm-close-tiddler`), the engine routes them through the navigator widget found under `$tw.pageWidgetNode`. Messages with global rootWidget handlers (`tm-save-wiki`, custom messages) work without any routing.
* To find every action tiddler your wiki currently ships, filter for `[all[shadows+tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action]]`.

! Visual grouping (clusters)

The engine clusters items in the result list by their contributing plugin so that, e.g., orga-palette entries are visually separated from appify entries in the root stage. The cluster label is derived as:

# Explicit `ca-group` field on the entry/action, if present.
# Otherwise the contributing plugin's `name` field (looked up via `$tw.wiki.getShadowSource(title)` → plugin tiddler → `name`).
# Falls back to the plugin title with `$:/plugins/` stripped, or `""` for user-authored (non-shadow) tiddlers.

Headers are ''suppressed'' when a stage contains only one cluster — so a single-plugin action menu still looks like a flat list. Use `ca-group` to override:

* Group items from several plugins under a shared header: set the same `ca-group: Mutations` on each of them.
* Push items from one plugin into a different cluster: set `ca-group` to that cluster's label.

Cluster ordering follows the lowest `ca-order` member of each cluster — the same single-knob ordering model as un-grouped items.

! Detail templates

The details drawer (shown while Ctrl is held, or always-on via Settings) prepends help text (`ca-help` overrides `ca-hint`) and renders ''detail templates'' — wikitext tiddlers tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/template`''. A template applies to the picked row when its `ca-template-applies` filter returns the picked title (the filter runs with `currentTiddler` bound to the picked title; omit the filter for a universal template).

When multiple templates apply, a tab strip appears above the body and `←/→` switches tabs (when details has focus).

The template's wikitext is rendered with `currentTiddler` bound to the picked tiddler title, so all the usual transclusion syntax works: `{{!!ca-name}}`, `<<currentTiddler>>`, `[<currentTiddler>has[ca-kind]]`, etc.

```
title: $:/plugins/example/templates/orga-person
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/template
ca-template-name: Person
ca-template-applies: [<currentTiddler>rrt.type[person]]
ca-order: 20

''<<currentTiddler>>''

;Teams
:<$list filter="[<currentTiddler>get[team-member-of]enlist-input[]]"><$link/><br></$list>

;Recent meetings
:<$list filter="[<currentTiddler>backlinks[]rrt.type[meeting]limit[5]]"><$link/><br></$list>
```

If no template applies and no help text is set, the drawer falls back to a raw fields-table for diagnostics.

! Confirm drills

DEL/Backspace on certain rows pushes a synthetic ''confirm stage'' with two leaves: Confirm and Cancel. The destructive ''consequence'' is shown as the inline hint of the Confirm row AND in the details drawer banner. Selection defaults to Cancel; the user must explicitly arrow down to Confirm and press Enter.

Triggered automatically by the engine in two scenarios:
* ''Overridden setting:'' DEL on a row whose `ca-bind-tiddler` has both a shadow AND a real (override) tiddler. Confirm deletes the override; the shadow default is restored.
* ''Non-shadow tiddler in a diagnostic list:'' DEL on a dynamic-item row whose title points to a user-authored tiddler. Confirm deletes the tiddler. Backlink count is shown pre-confirm.

Or, explicitly via row-level fields (synthetic JSON items — `ca-items-from`):

;`ca-on-delete`
:Wikitext fired when DEL/Backspace is pressed on this row. Receives `<<picked>>` and `<<parent-picked>>` in scope. Takes priority over the built-in restore-default / delete-tiddler paths above, so it's the right surface for "delete this synthetic row" semantics where the row represents a sub-entity (e.g. one element of a JSON array on a parent tiddler) rather than a tiddler.
;`ca-on-delete-consequence`
:Optional. If set, DEL pushes the confirm stage with this text as the consequence; if unset, the action fires immediately (no confirmation). Standard `<<picked>>` / `<<parent-picked>>` substitution.

Shadow-only rows (no override to restore) and built-in entry/action/setting rows (no `ca-bind-tiddler`, no `ca-on-delete`) are silent no-ops.

! Reorder gestures (`ca-on-move-up` / `ca-on-move-down`)

Symmetric with `ca-on-delete`, for synthetic JSON-array rows whose "move" means mutating the parent tiddler's array order. Two optional fields fire on Ctrl-↑ / Ctrl-↓ when the row has menu focus:

;`ca-on-move-up`
:Wikitext fired on Ctrl-↑. Receives `<<picked>>` (row title) and the usual `<<parent-picked>>` / `<<stage-N-picked>>` walk in scope.
;`ca-on-move-down`
:Wikitext fired on Ctrl-↓. Same scope.

cp pre-bumps `stage.selectedIndex` by ±1 before firing, so the user's selection follows the row through the change-hook's stage recompute (which preserves selectedIndex when the result count is unchanged). Bare ↑/↓ keep their selection-nudge semantics; rows that don't declare the action fall through to that. The action itself is responsible for being a no-op at array boundaries (cp doesn't gate the keystroke — at the top row `Ctrl-↑` still fires, and the action's own bounds check decides whether to mutate).

Used by ''rimir/kind'' to reorder fields in a kind's `kind.fields` JSON array — the field-list rendering order IS the form field order, so a reorder propagates to instances and to the side-preview form.

! Pick-and-return leaves (`ca-after-fire: pop`)

By default a leaf's Enter fires its `ca-actions` and ''closes'' the palette. For single-select sub-drills inside a multi-field edit flow — e.g. a ref/enum picker that sits next to other field rows on the parent stage — closing the palette breaks the flow: the user wants to land back on the field-edit stage with their pick applied, ready to edit the next field.

Add `ca-after-fire: pop` to those leaves. The engine then fires the action, pops the picker stage, and keeps the palette open on the parent stage. Used by `rimir/kind` for its ref / enum single-select sub-drills.

```
ca-name: My First Node
ca-kind: leaf
ca-after-fire: pop
ca-actions: <$action-setfield $tiddler="$:/state/example/draft" $field="parent" $value="My First Node"/>
```

! Bound drills (right-aligned current value)

When a drill row carries `ca-bind-tiddler` + `ca-bind-field`, the palette renders the currently-bound value on the right of the row — like a text/number/date row — so the user sees their pick without re-entering the drill. References are resolved via the target tiddler's `caption` field (falling back to the raw title). Multi-select string-array binds are comma-joined for compactness. Empty binds render `(unset)`.

! Sensitivity of stage-state

Stages are populated by re-running `ca-next-scope` whenever the user types in the input. Filters that hit ''many'' tiddlers can be slow if you're searching the entire wiki on every keystroke — prefer a tighter base set (`[rrt.type[...]]` first, then `+[search<query>]`) over a broad search of all titles.

! Filters & Visibility (declarative constraints)

The palette has two parallel constraint kinds, each surfacing its own pill strip:

* A ''filter'' is a tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/filter`''. Its expression is appended (intersected) to every result-list filter — it ''narrows what's shown''. Filter pills sit in a blue strip.
* A ''visibility'' rule is a tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/visibility`''. Its expression is a predicate evaluated against each root-entry title — non-empty result means ''hide that entry from the root menu''. Visibility pills sit in an orange/red strip.

The two kinds share grammar (prefix + arg) and shape (chip / hint / help / order). Differences are limited to which pipeline stage their expression feeds into.

! Adding & removing constraints

Three input paths (filters and visibility share these):

* ''Prefix typing.'' Each constraint declares an optional prefix. Type the prefix in the search input, then the argument, then Enter to commit the pill — the input picks up a colour cue (blue for filter, orange for visibility) and a hint while a prefix matches. E.g. `/parser` → search-text filter pill with arg `parser`; `hide:appify` → hide-group visibility pill with arg `appify`.
* ''Add via message.'' Send the rootWidget message ''`rimir-cascade-palette-add-filter`'' / ''`rimir-cascade-palette-add-visibility`'' with a ''`filter`'' / ''`visibility`'' param naming the tiddler. The input is pre-filled with the constraint's prefix so the user can type the argument and Enter to commit.
* ''Shift-DEL on a root entry'' adds a ''Hide selected entry'' visibility pill with the picked entry as its argument.

Removal:

* ''Focus the strip'' (Tab cycle includes `visibility` and `filter` whenever those strips have content).
* ''`←` / `→`'' move between pills within the focused strip.
* ''DEL'' / ''Backspace'' removes the focused pill.
* ''Ctrl-DEL'' (any focus section) clears ''both'' strips.
* ''Reset constraints'' leader (`x` key, idle 500ms) — same effect as Ctrl-DEL.

Pills ''persist within session'' — closing and reopening the palette keeps both strips intact. A full page reload clears everything.

! Filter tiddler fields

;`ca-filter-name`
:Display name shown in help readouts. Required.
;`ca-filter-prefix`
:Short string that triggers the filter from the input (e.g. `/`, `#`, `prefix:`, `@`). Optional — filters without a prefix can only be added via the add-filter message.
;`ca-filter-arg`
:How the trailing input is interpreted: `text` (free-text), `tag`, `tiddler`, or `none`. Drives sanitisation. Default: `text`.
;`ca-filter-expr`
:TW filter snippet appended (intersected) with every result-list filter. Use ''`<arg>`'' as the operand placeholder — the engine substitutes the user's argument as `[<arg>]` at pill-push time. E.g. ''`+[prefix<arg>]`'' → `+[prefix[work/]]` for `prefix:work/`.
;`ca-filter-chip`
:Plain-text template for the pill label. Use ''`<<arg>>`'' for argument substitution. Defaults to `ca-filter-name` when omitted.
;`ca-filter-hint`
:One-line tooltip shown on pill hover.
;`ca-filter-help`
:Multi-line help text shown in the details pane when the pill is focused. Falls back to `ca-filter-hint` when omitted.
;`ca-order`
:Sort key.

! Visibility tiddler fields

Identical shape with the `ca-filter-*` prefix replaced by `ca-visibility-*`:

;`ca-visibility-name`
:Display name.
;`ca-visibility-prefix`
:Short string that triggers it from the input (e.g. `hide:`). Optional.
;`ca-visibility-arg`
:`text` / `tag` / `tiddler` / `none`. Default: `text`.
;`ca-visibility-expr`
:''Predicate filter''. Evaluated per root-entry with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the entry title; if non-empty result, the entry is hidden. Use ''`<arg>`'' for the operand placeholder. E.g. ''`[<currentTiddler>get[ca-group]match<arg>]`'' hides entries whose `ca-group` field matches the typed argument.
;`ca-visibility-chip` / `ca-visibility-hint` / `ca-visibility-help` / `ca-order`
:Display fields (same shape as filter).

! Replacement semantics

At most ''one pill per backing tiddler'' is active at a time, within each kind. Adding a new instance evicts any prior instance with the same backing tiddler — so typing `prefix:work/` then `prefix:private/` leaves only the second filter pill on the strip. The ''Hide selected entry'' visibility is the exception: its per-instance key is augmented with the hidden title so multiple hide-entry pills coexist (one per hidden entry).

! Context tiddler

The palette captures the tiddler the user was looking at when the hotkey fired (focused `[data-tiddler-title]` ancestor, falling back to `$:/HistoryList`'s last entry). It is exposed to ''every'' filter/visibility expression and action as `<<context-tiddler>>` — independent of any visible pill. The `@` filter is an opt-in that turns the captured tiddler (or a typed override) into a visible filter pill.

! Worked example — Title-prefix filter

```
title: $:/plugins/example/filters/title-prefix
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/filter
ca-filter-name: Restrict to title prefix
ca-filter-prefix: prefix:
ca-filter-arg: text
ca-filter-expr: +[prefix<arg>]
ca-filter-chip: prefix: <<arg>>
ca-filter-hint: Keep only tiddlers whose title starts with the given string.
```

Type `prefix:work/` → pill ''`prefix: work/`'' appears, every result list now intersects with `[prefix[work/]]`. Type `prefix:private/` afterwards → the old pill is replaced (per-kind uniqueness).

! Worked example — Hide a group (visibility)

```
title: $:/plugins/example/visibility/hide-group
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/visibility
ca-visibility-name: Hide a group
ca-visibility-prefix: hide:
ca-visibility-arg: text
ca-visibility-expr: [<currentTiddler>get[ca-group]match<arg>]
ca-visibility-chip: hide: <<arg>>
ca-visibility-hint: Remove entries with this group from the root menu.
```

Type `hide:appify` → pill ''`hide: appify`'' appears in the visibility strip; every entry with `ca-group: appify` is hidden from the root menu (other stages unaffected).

! Prefix collision rules

Prefix matching is ''greedy by length'', across both filter and visibility tag families. With `/` (filter) and `prefix:` (filter) and `hide:` (visibility) all declared, typing `prefix:foo` matches the `prefix:` filter (longer match wins). Ties between two same-length prefixes use the tiddler iteration order (alphabetical by title) — declare different prefixes if disambiguation matters.

! Views (multi-view root menu)

A ''view'' is a tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view`'' that describes how to build the root menu. Each registered view shows as a pill in the ''view strip''; the active view is highlighted. The strip is hidden when fewer than two views are declared.

The plugin ships four views out of the box:

* ''Entries'' (default) — plugin-declared entry tiddlers (the prior behaviour).
* ''All tiddlers'' — flat list of non-system tiddlers.
* ''By namespace'' — tree built by splitting tiddler titles on `/`. Drill into containers.
* ''By parent'' — TW tag-tree: walks `tags[0]` ancestor chain up to `TableOfContents`.

! Switching views

* ''Click'' a pill — activates that view; stage stack pops to root; menu rebuilds.
* ''Tab into the view strip'', ''←/→'' to highlight a pill, ''Enter'' or ''Space'' to activate.
* ''Esc'' from the strip returns focus to the input without activating.

Active view persists ''session-only'' — page reload returns to the `ca-view-default: yes` view.

! View tiddler fields

;`ca-view-name`
:Display name on the pill and as the root breadcrumb segment. Required.
;`ca-view-hint`
:Tooltip on hover. Optional.
;`ca-view-default`
:Set to `yes` on exactly one view — the initial selection on page load.
;`ca-view-roots`
:Filter producing the root rows. No `<currentTiddler>` binding. E.g. `[all[shadows+tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry]]` for Entries, `[!is[system]]` for All tiddlers, `[!is[system]cp-child-of[]]` for the namespace tree's root level. Required.
;`ca-view-source`
:Back-compat alias for `ca-view-roots` (honoured when `ca-view-roots` is absent). Use on flat views authored before the rename.
;`ca-view-children`
:Filter producing the direct children of a node, evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the parent tiddler title. Empty = flat view (every root row is a leaf, no descent). E.g. `[tag<currentTiddler>]` for a tag-tree, `[!is[system]cp-child-of<currentTiddler>]` for a path-segment tree.
;`ca-view-leaf`
:Optional leaf-test filter, evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the candidate node. Truthy result ⇒ the node is a leaf (no drill chevron, Enter fires actions). Default behaviour: a node is a leaf iff `ca-view-children` returns empty for it.
;`ca-view-label`
:Optional display-name filter, evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the node. Default precedence: `caption` field → last `/`-segment of title → bare title.
;`ca-view-sort`
:`alphabetical` (default) \| `natural` (numeric-aware) \| `by-field` \| `custom`.
;`ca-view-sort-field`
:Field name used by `sort: by-field`. Numeric values sort numerically; otherwise locale-compared.
;`ca-view-sort-key`
:Per-row filter returning a sortable key. Used by `sort: custom`. Receives `<currentTiddler>` bound to the row's source.
;`ca-view-containers-first`
:`yes` (default for tree views) \| `no`. Containers float above leaves at each tree level as a stable post-sort.
;`ca-view-show-count`
:`yes` \| `no` (default). Render a child-count badge on tree-container rows.
;`ca-view-count-format`
:Badge template, default ` (<<count>>)`. The `<<count>>` token is substituted with the integer child count.
;`ca-view-row-name` / `ca-view-row-hint` / `ca-view-row-icon` / `ca-view-row-kind` / `ca-view-row-group` / `ca-view-row-order`
:Per-source TW filters that ''override'' the named field on each row, evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the source. Unset filters fall through to the source tiddler's own `ca-*` field — so the Entries view doesn't need to declare any row-* override (entries already carry the right fields).
;`ca-view-row-next-scope` / `ca-view-row-items-from`
:Same dual-mode as the entry/action fields, but provided ''per source'' via filter. Used when drill items should fan out into a stage configured per-source.
;`ca-view-row-actions`
:Wikitext fired when the user picks a leaf row. Receives `<<currentTiddler>>` (= the source tiddler title) at fire time. ''Dual-mode'': if the value parses as a TW filter that returns a result, the result is used as the action wikitext (lets the Entries view fetch the entry's own `ca-actions` via `[<currentTiddler>get[ca-actions]]`); otherwise the raw value is used as a wikitext template directly (lets the All tiddlers view declare `<$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>` without `[[…]]` wrapping).
;`ca-order`
:Position in the view strip (left → right by `ca-order` ascending).

! Per-view entry positioning

Existing entry tiddlers can opt into per-view placement by declaring ''`ca-position-<view-slug>`'' fields. The slug is the basename of the view tiddler (e.g. `by-namespace` from `$:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/views/by-namespace`). Falls back to ''`ca-position`'' (applies to all views), then to ''`at-root`'' (default).

Values:

* ''`at-root`'' — entry appears at the root level of the view.
* ''`none`'' — entry excluded from this view entirely.
* ''`<tiddler-title>`'' — entry appears under the named tiddler when descent reaches it. The position is matched literally against the parent tiddler at each tree-stage.
* ''`<pos1> : <pos2>`'' or ''newline-separated'' — multi-position; entry appears at every listed position.

''Position semantics:'' nodes are tiddlers in the new model, so position values are tiddler titles, not synthetic path strings. `at-root` matches the root level for every view. To place an entry under `Tools/Search`, a tiddler titled `Tools/Search` must exist (and be reachable through the view's `roots`/`children` descent). If you need a virtual folder that has no backing tiddler, create the tiddler — e.g. an empty `Tools` and `Tools/Search` — so the tree has a node to descend into.

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/advanced-search
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Advanced Search
ca-actions: <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-show-switcher"/>
ca-position-by-namespace: $:/core/ui
ca-position-by-parent: SystemPalette
ca-position-all-tiddlers: none
```

! Multi-layer views

A view can compose multiple structure layers via ''`ca-view-layers`''. Each layer is a tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/structure-layer`'' carrying its own `ca-layer-roots` / `ca-layer-children` / row decorations. The descent merges layers' rows at every node — root and tree-stage alike — and the result-list sort applies uniformly across layers. Tree-stage drills pin to the originating layer so descent doesn't bleed across layers.

```
title: $:/plugins/example/views/work-overview
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view
ca-view-name: Work overview
ca-view-layers: $:/plugins/example/layers/projects $:/plugins/example/layers/inbox
ca-view-sort: by-field
ca-view-sort-field: ca-order

title: $:/plugins/example/layers/projects
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/structure-layer
ca-layer-name: Projects
ca-layer-roots: [tag[project]]
ca-layer-children: [tag<currentTiddler>tag[task]]
ca-layer-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-layer-row-entity-type: [<currentTiddler>tag[task]then[task]] [<currentTiddler>tag[project]then[project]]

title: $:/plugins/example/layers/inbox
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/structure-layer
ca-layer-name: Inbox
ca-layer-roots: [tag[inbox]!has[done]]
ca-layer-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-layer-row-entity-type: [[inbox-item]]
```

The view above shows projects (with their nested tasks under each) alongside an inbox list. ''Right-arrow'' on a task ''leaf'' opens the action-menu stage of type `task` — actions tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action` with `ca-entity-type: task` populate it. ''Space'' opens the same menu on any typed row — including containers (Projects) where Right-arrow keeps its descend-into-children semantic. So a project ''container'' is reached for actions via Space; an inbox ''leaf'' via either Right-arrow or Space.

Layer-name → default `ca-group` mapping kicks in automatically: with result-list grouping enabled, the menu shows section headers ''Projects'' and ''Inbox''. Per-row overrides (`ca-layer-row-group`) still take precedence when set.

''Built-in entries layer.'' Tree views (≥ 1 layer declaring `ca-layer-children`) automatically get a built-in synthetic ''entries'' layer appended last — that's how positioned entry tiddlers (`ca-position`) land in the result. Opt out per view via `ca-view-include-entries: no`. The Structure pill row shows this layer below the author-declared ones, rendered muted to flag its automatic origin.

! Custom tree shapes via the children filter

Anything you can express as "given a parent, what are its direct children?" is a one-line view. Examples:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/views/by-author
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view
ca-view-name: By author
ca-view-roots: [!is[system]has[author]get[author]] +[!is[blank]] +[unique[]]
ca-view-children: [!is[system]has[author]] :filter[get[author]match<currentTiddler>]
ca-view-leaf: [!is[system]has[author]is[tiddler]]
ca-view-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-order: 500
```

The example above produces a two-level tree: roots are distinct author names; children of each author are the tiddlers attributed to that author. The `ca-view-leaf` test forces tiddler rows to be leaves (since `:filter` would otherwise treat them as containers with no children).

''Performance note:'' tree views run the children filter once per drilled node and once per show-count badge (when enabled). The cost scales with the number of candidates the filter examines, not with the depth of the tree. Keep filters tight (lead with `!is[system]` / `[tag[...]]` / `[prefix[...]]` operators that benefit from TW's title index) for large stores.

! Axes — grouping chains on top of a structure-layer

A view's structure-layer can declare a chain of ''axes'' that bucket the layer's source set at the top of the descent. Each axis runs at one tree depth: depth 0 buckets `layer.roots` by the first axis, depth 1 buckets the parent-bucket-narrowed set by the second axis, and so on. Past the chain, the layer's normal `roots` / `children` filters take over — so axes ''compose'' with recursive trees rather than replacing them.

''Three useful configurations'' of a single layer:

|!Axes |!Children |!Behaviour |
|none |none |Flat list. Every row in `roots` is a leaf. |
|none |set |Pure recursive tree (today's ''By parent'', ''By namespace''). Axes never engage. |
|set |none |Pure grouping. Chain runs all the way down; leaves under the deepest axis are tiddlers from the narrowed source. |
|set |set |Bucket the source first, then under each leaf bucket each tiddler descends recursively via `children` as today. ''Mixed'' tree. |

''Axis tag:'' `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis`. ''Layer declaration:'' `ca-layer-axes` lists axis tiddler titles in chain order, space-separated. Implicit-layer views use `ca-view-axes` with the same semantics.

! Axis tiddler fields

;`ca-axis-name`
:Display name shown on chain pills + in the axis picker. Required.
;`ca-axis-hint`
:Detail-drawer help text shown when the axis pill is focused.
;`ca-axis-key`
:Filter evaluated per row with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the row tiddler; the first result is the bucket key. ''Required.'' Examples: `[get[created]format:date[YYYY]]`, `[get[status]]`, `[tags[]first[]]`. For parametric axes, reference `<axis-param-X>` widget variables (e.g. `[get<axis-param-field>]`).
;`ca-axis-label`
:Optional filter evaluated per bucket with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the bucket key; the first result is the display label. Falls back to the key itself.
;`ca-axis-sort`
:`first-seen` (default) — preserve source insertion order. `asc` / `desc` — localeCompare on key. `enum` — explicit order from `ca-axis-sort-keys` (keys outside the list sort after, alpha-ascending).
;`ca-axis-sort-keys`
:Space-separated key order, used by `enum` sort. E.g. for a month axis: `Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec`.
;`ca-axis-empty-label`
:Label shown for the synthetic empty bucket (rows where `ca-axis-key` resolves to empty/missing). Default `—`.
;`ca-axis-icon`
:Optional glyph displayed on bucket rows.

! Worked example — pure grouping by year / month / day

```
title: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-year-created
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis
ca-axis-name: Year (created)
ca-axis-key: [get[created]format:date[YYYY]]
ca-axis-sort: desc
ca-axis-empty-label: No date
```

```
title: $:/plugins/example/views/by-date
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view
ca-view-name: By date
ca-view-roots: [!is[system]!is[shadow]]
ca-view-axes: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-year-created $:/plugins/example/axes/by-month-created $:/plugins/example/axes/by-day-created
ca-view-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-view-show-count: yes
```

Open the palette, switch to ''By date'': year buckets at root, drill into a year → month buckets within, drill into a month → day buckets, drill into a day → tiddler leaves; Enter navigates.

! Worked example — mixed (axes + recursive children)

''By parent, sliced by year'' — TOC tiddlers grouped by year of creation, each TOC then expanding its tag-subtree:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/structure-layers/by-parent-by-year
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/structure-layer
ca-layer-name: By parent + year
ca-layer-roots: [tag[TableOfContents]]
ca-layer-children: [tag<currentTiddler>]
ca-layer-axes: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-year-created
ca-layer-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
```

Descent: root → year buckets containing TOC-tagged tiddlers. Drill ''2026'' → the TOC tiddlers created in 2026. Drill any TOC → its `tag<currentTiddler>` subtree, recursive — the axis chain is exhausted; from here on it's pure ''By parent''.

''Caveat — `layer.roots` does double duty.'' It's both the universe to bucket (during the chain) AND the forest roots at the transition. Pick the right set: `[!is[system]]` buckets every non-system tiddler AND every non-system tiddler becomes a recursive root; `[tag[TOC]]` keeps both phases TOC-only.

''Caveat — cross-bucket children.'' Past the transition, `layer.children` runs with `<currentTiddler>` = the parent ''tiddler''; date stops following you down. A 2025-tagged child of a 2026 TOC tiddler will appear in the 2026 subtree. If you need date-coherent descent, intersect a date predicate into `ca-layer-children`.

! Parametric axes

An axis whose `ca-axis-key` references `<axis-param-X>` is ''parametric'' — the chain entry carries a `params` map bound at evaluation time. The shipped ''by-field'' axis is the canonical example:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-field
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis
ca-axis-name: By field
ca-axis-key: [get<axis-param-field>]
ca-axis-sort: asc
```

When the user picks `by-field` from the axis picker, `_defaultParamsForAxis` scans the key filter for `<axis-param-X>` references and seeds an empty params map. The state tiddler then stores `{ "title": "$:/.../axes/by-field", "params": { "field": "" } }`. Editing the state tiddler directly to fill in `"field": "status"` (or any field name) activates the axis. A future picker iteration may prompt for params at add-time — for now the state is the editing surface.

! Pill UX for axes

The active chain renders in the Structure pill row, in each layer's mini-row: yellow ''by'' / ''→'' chain pills + a dashed ''+'' pill at the end. In expanded mode:

* ''Backspace / Delete'' removes the focused axis.
* ''Shift-← / Shift-→'' reorders within the chain.
* ''Enter'' on a chain pill opens the axis picker in ''replace'' mode.
* ''Enter / Space'' on the ''+'' pill opens the picker in ''append'' mode.

The picker is itself a cascade stage listing every tiddler tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis`. Esc cancels. On commit, the chain spec is written to `$:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/layer-axes/<slug>` and the strip is re-rendered with focus restored.

! Axis state — session override vs. declared default

Each layer's active chain is read in this order:

# Session state: `$:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/layer-axes/<slug>` (JSON `{"axes":[…]}`).
# Declared default: `ca-layer-axes` / `ca-view-axes` on the layer / view tiddler.

`<slug>` is the layer title's last `/`-segment (for explicit structure-layers) or the view title's last segment (for implicit layers). Deleting the state tiddler reverts the layer to its declared default — that's the ''reset'' affordance.

The `$:/state/...` namespace is NOT filesystem-synced — chain edits survive a reload but don't pollute the wiki on disk. Use the declared `ca-layer-axes` on a layer / view tiddler when you want the chain to ship with the plugin / wiki.

! Leader keys

A ''leader'' is a tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/leader`'' that binds a single character (or short string) to a wikitext action chain. Typing the key into the input and ''pausing for 500ms'' (the idle window) fires the actions. Any keystroke during the window cancels — `@foo` types four chars; `@` then idle fires the `@` leader.

Visual feedback while a leader is pending:

* The input picks up an ''amber underline''.
* The hint footer shows ''`↵ <key> — <ca-leader-hint>`''.
* The details pane (if open) renders ''`ca-leader-help`''.

After the leader fires:

* The input clears (so the user can keep typing / filtering naturally).
* Pills that changed (view / filter / visibility) ''flash briefly'' to signal what just happened.
* The leader's effects are visible through the standard strips — there's no special "leader mode" indicator to dismiss.

! Leader tiddler fields

;`ca-leader-key`
:The trigger string. Usually one character (`@`, `>`, `s`, `r`, `x`); multi-char allowed (`>>`). Matched against the FULL input — `@x` is "leader followed by typing", not a pending leader. Required.
;`ca-leader-name`
:Display name (used in any future leader-catalogue UI; optional).
;`ca-leader-hint`
:One-line hint shown in the footer during the idle window.
;`ca-leader-help`
:Multi-line help rendered in the details pane during the idle window. Falls back to hint.
;`ca-leader-idle-ms`
:Override the default 500ms idle window. Useful for multi-char leaders where a longer pause feels natural. Optional.
;`ca-leader-actions`
:Wikitext fired when the leader commits. Typically a chain of `<$action-sendmessage>` calls. Required.
;`ca-order`
:Sort key (for catalogue UIs; ordering doesn't affect dispatch).

! Widget messages usable in leader actions

|!Message |!Params |!Effect |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-set-view` |`view: <view-title>` |Activate the named view (same as clicking its pill). |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-add-filter` |`filter: <title>` |Push the named filter. For arg-type `none`, fires directly. For `text`/`tag`/`tiddler`, pre-fills the input with the filter's prefix so the user can type the argument and commit with Enter. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-set-filter` |`filter: <title>`, `arg: <value>` |Push the named filter with an explicit literal arg. Skips the interactive prefill — used by leaders that bake the arg in. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-add-visibility` |`visibility: <title>` |Same shape as add-filter but pushes onto the visibility strip. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-set-visibility` |`visibility: <title>`, `arg: <value>` |Same shape as set-filter but for visibility. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-reset-filters` |(none) |Clear every filter pill (leaves visibility alone). |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-reset-visibility` |(none) |Clear every visibility pill (leaves filters alone). |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-reset-constraints` |(none) |Clear ''both'' strips. Same as Ctrl-DEL globally. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-apply-preset` |`preset: <preset-title>` |Replay a preset: switch to its view, replace both filter and visibility lists with the preset's. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-save-preset` |(none) |Open the save mini-prompt — Enter commits, Esc cancels. |
|`rimir-cascade-palette-recall-preset` |(none) |Move focus to the preset pill strip. |

! Worked example — compound leader

```
title: $:/plugins/example/leaders/persons-mode
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/leader
ca-leader-key: @
ca-leader-name: Persons mode
ca-leader-hint: ↵ apply — Persons view + filter by type=person
ca-leader-help: Switch to a flat list of person tiddlers, narrowed to type=person. Useful when capturing notes about a person who is calling.
ca-leader-actions:
  <$action-sendmessage $message="rimir-cascade-palette-set-view" view="$:/plugins/example/views/persons-flat"/>
  <$action-sendmessage $message="rimir-cascade-palette-add-filter" filter="$:/plugins/example/filters/type-person"/>
ca-order: 100
```

Type `@`, pause 500ms → palette switches to Persons + the type-person filter pill appears with a brief amber flash. From there, type to filter the person list normally.

! Modal pick-mode views

A pick-mode view treats Enter on any row as ''commit the row's effective path as a filter arg''. Used by the `>` leader: switch to a tree picker, drill until you land on the desired path, hit Enter to commit a `prefix:` filter and return to the previous view.

Pick-mode is opt-in via two view fields:

;`ca-view-pick-mode`
:`yes` makes this view a pick-mode variant. Default empty.
;`ca-view-pick-emits-filter`
:Title of the filter tiddler to push when a row is committed. The filter's `ca-filter-expr` receives the row's effective path as `<arg>`.

What "effective path" means per row:

* Container row → the joined tree path (e.g. for the by-namespace strategy: ''`work/customers/A`'').
* Leaf row → the source tiddler title.

Behaviour:

* ''`→`'' (Right-arrow) on a container → drills (lets you narrow further before committing).
* ''Enter'' on any row (container OR leaf) → commits the path as filter arg, returns to prior view.
* ''Esc'' anywhere → cancel pick-mode, return to prior view, no pill pushed.

Pick-mode tracks a single return-target (`_pickModeReturnTo` in the widget). Chained pick-modes (one pick-mode view activating another) keep the original return-target, not the intermediate.

! Worked example — pick-mode view + matching leader

```
title: $:/plugins/example/views/by-namespace-pick
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view
ca-view-name: By namespace (pick)
ca-view-hint: Drill `/`-segments; Enter on any row commits the path as a title-prefix filter.
ca-view-source: [!is[system]]
ca-view-tree-strategy: path-segments
ca-view-pick-mode: yes
ca-view-pick-emits-filter: $:/plugins/example/filters/title-prefix
ca-view-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-order: 350
```

```
title: $:/plugins/example/leaders/by-namespace-pick
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/leader
ca-leader-key: >
ca-leader-name: Pick a namespace
ca-leader-hint: Switch to a tree picker; Enter commits the path as a title-prefix filter.
ca-leader-actions: <$action-sendmessage $message="rimir-cascade-palette-set-view" view="$:/plugins/example/views/by-namespace-pick"/>
ca-order: 200
```

! Presets

A ''preset'' captures the current `(active-view, filters, visibility)` under a name. Apply a preset to replay that state in one step. Tag: ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/preset`''.

Fields on a preset tiddler:

|!Field |!Purpose |
|`ca-preset-name` |Display name (e.g. "PersonsOfA") |
|`ca-preset-view` |Title of the view active at save time |
|`ca-preset-constraints` |JSON object `{"filters": [{title, arg}, …], "visibility": [{title, arg}, …]}` — both constraint lists at save time |
|`ca-order` |Sort key in the preset strip |

! Save flow (`s` leader)

# Press `s`, wait 500ms.
# The input is repurposed for one-line name entry — placeholder ''"Save preset as…"'', input picks up an emerald background.
# Type a name, press Enter. The widget writes a preset tiddler at ''`$:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/presets/<sanitised-slug>`''. If a tiddler at that title already exists, ''`-2`'', ''`-3`'', … are appended.
# Esc cancels.

! Recall flow (`r` leader)

# Press `r`, wait 500ms.
# Focus jumps to the preset pill strip at the top of the popup.
# Use `←` / `→` to select a preset, Enter to apply. The palette: clears current filters + visibility, pushes the preset's filters and visibility rules (looked up by title), switches to the preset's view.

If a preset references a deleted constraint tiddler, that constraint is skipped (warning to console). If it references a deleted view, the palette stays on its current view and rebuilds with the new constraint state. No data loss — presets are inspectable as regular tiddlers.

! Side preview pane

An entry/action can register a ''side preview'' that opens a right-column pane when the user drills into the row. The cascade column visually shrinks to 50% on the left; the pane renders an authored wikitext template against an entry-computed context. The pane stays visible while the drilled stage (or any deeper one) is on the stack, and disappears once the user pops back out — so the cascade fills 100% again.

Distinct from the ''detail'' drawer (Ctrl-hold or `details-always-on`): the detail drawer is bound to the currently-selected row and renders templates tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/template`''. The side preview is bound to ''what the user is editing'' — pinned at drill-time and kept stable as the user navigates inside.

! Two registration mechanisms (use either, or both)

! ! (a) Per-menu — declare on the entry/action

;`ca-preview-template`
:Title of a wikitext tiddler whose body is rendered in the right pane. Required to enable an explicit candidate.
;`ca-preview-context`
:Filter evaluated at drill-time in the parent stage's substitution scope (`<<picked>>`, `<<parent-picked>>`, `<<query>>`, `<<context-tiddler>>`, etc.). The first result becomes `<<currentTiddler>>` inside the preview template AND is exposed to deeper stages' substitution scope as `<<stage-preview-context>>`. Defaults to `<<picked>>` (the row being drilled into) — typical for actions where `<<picked>>` is the entity being acted upon.
;`ca-preview-title`
:Optional caption shown in the colored title strip above the preview body. Empty value keeps the strip hidden.
;`ca-preview-name`
:Optional pill label when multiple candidates are visible at once. Default derived from the template title.
;`ca-preview-per-row`
:When `yes`, the active context tracks the currently-selected row's title — live ↑/↓ updates. Used by browse lists.

''Tag-only opt-in.'' If you want the side-preview pane to activate but don't have a specific template in mind, omit `ca-preview-template` and set just `ca-preview-context` (or `ca-preview-per-row: yes`). The pane will populate purely from ''tag-based candidates'' (below) that match the resolved context. Useful for entity-browsing entries that want auto-attached previews.

! ! (b) Tag-based — declare a self-contained template + applicability filter

Any tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/side-preview`'' is a candidate that auto-attaches to the preview pane whenever the active context matches its `ca-preview-applies` filter. The tagged tiddler is BOTH the registration AND (by default) the template body — no separate template tiddler needed.

;`ca-preview-applies`
:Filter evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` bound to the active context. Returns non-empty → this candidate applies. Empty / missing = always applies (rarely what you want).
;`ca-preview-template`
:Optional override pointing at a separate template tiddler. Defaults to the tagged tiddler's own title.
;`ca-preview-name`
:Pill label. Default derived from the template title.
;`ca-preview-title`
:Optional caption shown in the colored title strip above the body.
;`ca-preview-order`
:Sort key among tag candidates. Default `100`. Lower = earlier.

When per-menu and tag-based mechanisms BOTH contribute candidates against the same context, all candidates show as pills in a horizontal row at the top of the pane (per-menu first, then tag candidates by `ca-preview-order`). The active pill is highlighted. ←/→ when focus is on the preview cycles between them (also click). With a single candidate the pill row is suppressed entirely.

! Worked example — Edit kind's fields with a live form preview

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/kind/edit-fields
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: kind
ca-name: Edit fields
ca-kind: drill
ca-items-from: [function[kind.cascade-fields-for-edit],<parent-picked>]
ca-next-title: Fields of <<parent-picked>>
ca-preview-template: $:/plugins/example/templates/kind-form-preview
ca-preview-context: [<picked>]
ca-preview-title: Form preview
```

```
title: $:/plugins/example/templates/kind-form-preview
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

! Form for <<currentTiddler>>

A form rendered from this kind's current field set. As you add / remove / edit fields in the cascade, this preview re-renders live.

<$transclude tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/kind/view"/>
```

Drilling into "Edit fields" pushes the field-edit stage AND attaches the preview. Each time the user edits the kind tiddler (the context — its `kind.fields` array changes), the wiki change-hook invalidates the cache and the pane re-renders.

! Lifecycle

* Preview attaches when the user drills via Right-arrow / Enter / Space into a row that carries `ca-preview-template`.
* While the registering stage is anywhere on the stack, the pane stays visible.
* Drilling DEEPER (pushing another stage) inherits the same preview — `<<stage-preview-context>>` is the resolved context.
* Popping past the registering stage hides the pane and restores the cascade to 100%.
* If a deeper stage ALSO declares `ca-preview-template`, that one takes over while it's on the stack (topmost wins).
* Closing the palette clears the preview cache entirely.

! Focus & interactivity

The pane joins the Tab cycle as a new focus section ''`preview`'' (only when visible). Esc returns to input; arrow-up/down let the browser scroll natively. Mousedown on the pane background grabs focus, but clicks on form inputs / buttons / links inside the rendered template pass through — the template is fully interactive.

! Limitations & follow-ups

* ''Editing presets'' — no in-palette UI for rename / delete. Use the wiki normally (preset tiddlers are real tiddlers).
* ''Compose presets'' — applying a preset always ''replaces'' both constraint lists. There's no "apply on top of existing state".
* ''Side-preview tabs'' — only a single preview template per entry/action right now. Tag-based discovery (à la detail templates) is a possible follow-up if multiple plugins want to register competing previews on the same drill.

! Row icons (`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon`)

A row-icon is a small glyph rendered in a footer strip below the main line of any tiddler-bearing row. Use it to surface affordances on the row's backing tiddler — opening an external URL, jumping to an attachment, copying a value, etc. — without crowding the name / value slots. The strip renders only when at least one icon resolves for the row; rows with no applicable icons look identical to before.

! ! Built-in: URL icon

The plugin ships ''`row-icons/url.tid`'' (key `url`) that surfaces a ''🌐'' glyph on any row whose backing tiddler carries a URL value in one of the configured fields. The scanned field list lives at ''`$:/config/rimir/cascade-palette/url-fields`'' — default `url`, space-separated for multiple (e.g. `url website homepage`). The first field whose value matches ''`/^(?:https?|ftp|ftps|mailto|tel):/i`'' wins; trailing whitespace is trimmed.

Two gestures on the same row:

* ''Alt-↵'' (or click the glyph) opens the URL in a new browser tab — `window.open(url, "_blank", "noopener,noreferrer")`.
* ''Ctrl-Alt-↵'' copies the URL to the clipboard via `$tw.utils.copyToClipboard(url)` (TW core helper — handles both the modern Clipboard API and the legacy `execCommand` fallback, emits a tm-notify on success / failure).

The row's normal Enter / Ctrl-Enter behaviour is unchanged.

! ! Author your own

Tag a tiddler with `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon` and declare:

;`ca-row-icon-key`
:Symbolic id (`url`, `attachment`, `linear-ticket`, ...). The key `url` triggers the built-in field-scanning resolver. Other keys must declare `ca-row-icon-applies` (the gate) + optionally `ca-row-icon-payload` (the value bound to `<<payload>>` when the icon fires).
;`ca-row-icon-glyph`
:Display character / emoji. Default `•`.
;`ca-row-icon-hint`
:Tooltip on hover. The runtime appends ` · Alt-↵ or click` so the gesture is discoverable.
;`ca-row-icon-applies`
:Filter — `<currentTiddler>` is the row's tiddler title. Non-empty result = the icon shows. Required for non-`url` keys.
;`ca-row-icon-payload`
:Optional filter — first result is bound to `<<payload>>` when the icon fires. Use this when your action wants to act on a specific field's value rather than the tiddler title.
;`ca-row-icon-action`
:Optional wikitext actions. Fired with `<<payload>>` + `<<row-icon-key>>` + the standard stage variables (`<<picked>>`, `<<parent-picked>>`, `<<currentTiddler>>` bound to the row).
;`ca-row-icon-message`
:Optional built-in JS dispatch key for the ''primary'' gesture (Alt-↵ / click). Currently recognised: `open-url` (`window.open(payload, "_blank", "noopener,noreferrer")`), `copy-payload` (`$tw.utils.copyToClipboard(payload)`). May coexist with `ca-row-icon-action` (both fire).
;`ca-row-icon-alt-action`
:Optional wikitext actions fired by the ''secondary'' gesture — ''Ctrl-Alt-↵'' on the row. Receives the same variables as `ca-row-icon-action` plus `<<row-icon-mode>>: "alt"` (so a single action can branch on which gesture fired it).
;`ca-row-icon-alt-message`
:Optional built-in JS dispatch key for the secondary gesture. Same vocabulary as `ca-row-icon-message`. The shipped 🌐 icon uses `copy-payload` here to put the URL on the clipboard.
;`ca-row-icon-alt-hint`
:Tooltip text for the secondary gesture. Shown on a second line of the glyph's hover tooltip suffixed with `· Ctrl-Alt-↵`.
;`ca-row-icon-primary`
:`yes` = preferred target for the row-level ''Alt-↵'' keyboard gesture when multiple icons apply. If no icon is `primary`, the first applicable icon (by `ca-row-icon-order`) wins.
;`ca-row-icon-order`
:Display order in the strip (lower first, default `100`).

! ! Worked example — Linear ticket link

```
title: $:/plugins/example/row-icons/linear
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon
ca-row-icon-key: linear
ca-row-icon-glyph: 🔗
ca-row-icon-hint: Open Linear ticket
ca-row-icon-applies: [<currentTiddler>has[linear-ticket]]
ca-row-icon-payload: [<currentTiddler>get[linear-ticket]addprefix[https://linear.app/team/issue/]]
ca-row-icon-message: open-url
ca-row-icon-order: 20
```

Any tiddler carrying a `linear-ticket` field gets a 🔗 in its row-icon strip. Alt-↵ (or clicking the glyph) constructs the URL and opens it in a new tab.

! ! Worked example — Wiki-internal action

```
title: $:/plugins/example/row-icons/edit-raw
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon
ca-row-icon-key: edit-raw
ca-row-icon-glyph: ✎
ca-row-icon-hint: Open the raw editor
ca-row-icon-applies: [<currentTiddler>!is[system]]
ca-row-icon-action: <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-edit-tiddler" $param=<<currentTiddler>>/>
```

Surfaces a ✎ on every non-system tiddler; Alt-↵ fires `tm-edit-tiddler` via the navigator.

! Reach pills (`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/reach`)

Reach pills configure WHERE the search input walks. Same push / remove / DEL grammar as filter and visibility pills, just a separate strip with its own tag family and a teal accent. A reach-tagged tiddler declares:

;`ca-reach-name`
:Display name in the help pane.
;`ca-reach-mode`
:`here` (walk the subtree under the current stage) or `everywhere` (walk from the active view's root). Reach pills are ''mutually exclusive'' — pushing any reach pill evicts every other reach pill, so only one scope is ever active.
;`ca-reach-chip`
:Plain-text pill label. Defaults to the reach-name.
;`ca-reach-hint` / `ca-reach-help`
:Hover tooltip / details-pane help.

''Push via:'' the ''`rimir-cascade-palette-add-reach`'' message with param ''`reach: <tiddler-title>`''. Leaders d / g are the shipped shortcuts.

! Search-meta pills (`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/search-meta`)

Search-meta pills configure WHICH cascade-item author meta keys the matcher reads (the row's `name`, `hint`, and any author-defined slots populated by cp-items.js or a custom row-builder). Same grammar as reach pills, separate strip, violet accent. A pill-tagged tiddler declares:

;`ca-meta-key`
:The cascade-item property the pill represents (e.g. `name`, `hint`, or any author-defined key the cascade-item builder populates).
;`ca-chip` / `ca-hint` / `ca-help`
:Display chip / tooltip / details-pane help.

When at least one Search-meta pill is active, the matcher walks the UNION of those meta keys, ignoring per-row `ca-search-fields` and global default. No meta pills active → matcher uses each row's `ca-search-fields` declaration, falling back to global default at `$:/config/rimir/cascade-palette/search-fields-default`.

''Push via:'' ''`rimir-cascade-palette-add-meta`'' with param ''`meta: <tiddler-title>`''.

! Search-field pills (`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/search-field`)

Search-field pills configure WHICH literal tiddler fields the matcher reads on the row's backing tiddler. Same grammar as reach / meta pills, separate strip, amber accent. Synthetic rows (no backing tiddler) silently skip every Field pill. A pill-tagged tiddler declares:

;`ca-tiddler-field`
:The tiddler field name to read via `wiki.getTiddler(item.title).fields[<name>]`. Any field works: `text`, `caption`, `tags`, `modifier`, author-defined.
;`ca-chip` / `ca-hint` / `ca-help`
:Same shape as Meta.

Array-typed fields (like `tags`) are flattened to a space-separated string before substring matching.

When at least one Search-field pill is active, the matcher unions the tiddler-field layer with the meta layer. No field pills active → the tiddler-field layer is skipped entirely (keeps the default search cheap).

''Push via:'' ''`rimir-cascade-palette-add-field`'' with param ''`field: <tiddler-title>`''.

! Item-level search authoring (`ca-search-*` on cascade items)

;`ca-search-fields`
:Space-separated list of cascade-item meta keys the matcher walks for THIS row. Default per global config.
;`ca-search-skip`
:When `yes`, the deep walker excludes this row from results AND does not descend its subtree. Default auto-skip applies to `text`, `number`, `date`, `toggle`, and `confirm` row kinds.

Authoring example:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/find-things
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Find things
ca-hint: Search across projects, tasks, notes.
ca-kind: drill
ca-next-scope: [tag[work]]
```

! In-palette help (`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/help`)

Help sections are tiddlers tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/help`. They appear as rows in the ''Help'' entry (also reachable via the `?` leader). Each row's body wikitext renders in the side preview as the user navigates ↑/↓ — this is the standard `ca-preview-template` machinery with `ca-preview-per-row: yes`.

''Schema'' (standard cascade-item fields — no `ca-help-*` namespace):

|!Field |!Purpose |
|`ca-name` |Display name in the row |
|`ca-icon` |Glyph |
|`ca-group` |Category for visual grouping in the Help drill. Use `Plugin: <slug>` to land in the ''Plugins'' sub-drill. |
|`ca-order` |Sort order (lower first) |
|`ca-hint` |One-line subtitle (shown in the row's hint slot) |
|`ca-kind` |`leaf` (default) or `drill`. Drills declare their own `ca-next-scope`. |
|`text` |Wikitext body rendered in the side preview |

''Where to put the tiddler'':

* ''In a plugin'' — `$:/plugins/<author>/<plugin>/help` (one tiddler per plugin convention).
* ''In a wiki'' — any title works.

''Worked example — a plugin contribution'':

```
title: $:/plugins/example/help
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/help
ca-name: example
ca-icon: 🧪
ca-group: Plugin: example
ca-order: 10
ca-hint: What the example plugin adds to the palette.

|!Adds |!Activation |
|`x` leader |drills into Examples |
|`Examples` entry |root-level browser |

→ Full docs: <$link to="$:/plugins/example/doc/overview">example overview</$link>
```

Plugin-contributed leaders / pills / entries already appear automatically in the core ''Keys'' / ''Pills'' / ''Entries'' help sections via `<$list filter="...">` over the existing protocol tags — the per-plugin help tiddler is just narrative context.

! Limitations & follow-ups

* ''Editing presets'' — no in-palette UI for rename / delete. Use the wiki normally (preset tiddlers are real tiddlers).
* ''Compose presets'' — only one preset at a time.
* ''Action-menu walking'' — deep search doesn't currently descend into action menus, only entity and drill rows. Authors who want actions reachable from search can wire them via `ca-items-from` synthetic rows.
* ''Per-keystroke memo cache'' — each keystroke recomputes the deep walk; caps keep this fast. A memo invalidated by the wiki change hook is on the roadmap.
* ''Result ranking'' — deep results are in BFS-natural order (shallower matches first; same-depth keeps the cascade's sort). Exact-match boost and other ranking are Phase 2.
